\b Comparison between  Waterfall and Agile methodologies.\par
Waterfall \b0 is a sequential and linear approach to software development. It divides the development process into phases. i.e.  planning, design, implementation, testing, deployment, and maintenance.\par
\par
\b Agile methodology \b0 is an iterative and incremental approach to software development that emphasizes flexibility, collaboration, and customer feedback.Development is broken into small, manageable units.\par
\b Flexibility\b0 : Waterfall is rigid and change-resistant; Agile embraces change and continuous improvement.\par
\b Documentation: \b0 Waterfall emphasizes detailed documentation, whereas Agile focuses more on working software and less on exhaustive documentation.\par
\b Testing: \b0 In Waterfall, testing is done after development, while Agile integrates testing throughout the development cycle.\par
\b Customer Involvement\b0 : Waterfall typically involves customers early in the process, while Agile requires ongoing customer involvement\par
\b  Scenarios where each  approach would be appropriate:\b0\par
