\b  Common challenges faced by software engineers\par
\b0 1. The rapid advancement of technology\par
Rapid advancement in technology creates additional pressure on software developers. To adapt to this new trends  and  have competitive advantage becomes a problem.\par
This can be overcomed by Performing proper market research and competitors' analysis\par
2. Increasing customer demands in the development stage\par
The increasing demand of customers is among the software engineering coding challenges faced  by developers.\par
3. Time limitation\par
The deadlines set for developers to complete a task are incredibly short and this is one of the major challenges faced by programmers\par
4. Understanding the large and complex system requirements is difficult\par
Engineers face challenges when dealing with customers who have personal ideas about the software they want to use. And since there might be no direct contact this becomes a challenge.\par
This can be overcome Creating informative and well-structured conversations with end consumers\par
5. Rapid Technological Change\par
Developers  are required  to advance and update their skills to keep pace with the rapid evolution of technology. New programming languages, frameworks, and tools frequently come up, making it challenging to keep on upgrading.\par
\b Different types of testing and their importance in software quality assurance.\par
\b0 1. Unit testing\par
This is where each component is tested individually to ensure its functionality. This helps to determine whether the application functions as designed. The importance of this testing phase is that it can be run every time a piece of code is changed, allowing issues to be resolved as quickly as possible.\par
2.  Integration Testing\par
Allow software developers to test group units integrated into the system. It helps identify issues arising from coding errors or integration between modules. \par
3.  System Testing\par
This one tests the whole application where all components are assessed against specific business requirements. It evaluates whether the system has complied with all of the outlined requirements and sees that it meets Quality standards.\par
4. Acceptance Testing\par
This involves testing the system\rquote s Functional and Non-functional aspects, such as performance,  accessibility, compatibility, reliability. security and usability.It ensures that the system is ready for deployment.\par
